### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

Currently `Validators.required` works so you can enter a `space` character and form would become valid. Therefore, we need to use a custom `required` validator
```ts
public static required({ value }: AbstractControl): ValidationErrors | null {
    return String(value ?? '').trim() ? null : { required: true };
}
```

But that is causing issues with material form fields, the `required` asterisks are not displayed near to the label because this check does not pass
![image](https://github.com/angular/angular/assets/32300784/fe9aac08-ef3a-43c2-affb-cb28061125df)

### Proposed solution

Can you add an option to pass some boolean flag (ignore spaces or something) when initializing this validator or add some `strictlyRequired` validator in addition to avoid modifying existing one?

### Alternatives considered

Currently we have to use this work-around simply to override `required` asterisks.
```ts
public get hasRequiredValidator(): boolean {
    return !!this.control.validator?.({} as AbstractControl)?.required;
}
```

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

compiler-cli, compiler, core

### Description

The new Control Flow in Angular enhances template management, but it lacks a direct way to include external HTML files with scope binding. An `@include` feature, like `@include('./example.html', item)`, would enable including 'example.html' in the template, using the local `item` variable.


### Proposed solution

Introduce an `@include` directive in Angular:

```html
@include('./example.html', {item: someItem, item2: otherItem})
```

In 'example.html', use an `@input(){}` block to bind to `item`:

```html
@input(item) {
  <h1>{{ item.title }}</h1>
  <p>{{ item.description}}</p>
}

@input(item2) {
  <h1>{{ item2.title }}</h1>
  <p>{{ item2.description}}</p>
}
```

This allows directly including HTML content with scope binding, without creating a full component.

### Alternatives considered

The current method involves creating full components for reusable sections. This can be overkill for simple template parts, leading to unnecessary complexity.

### Is this a regression?

- [ ] Yes, this behavior used to work in the previous version

